08-13-2017 13-53-38 Omar Abouelkhair The question in the article is specific to whether the state is the guarantor but in he reply the sheikh says "It makes no difference whether the riba is with the state or with institutions belonging to it or with people in general. "
08-13-2017 13-56-40 Baraa Elabed Omar, you may be right that it is not permissible but note that the scholars who gave a dispensation for student loans did not do it on the basis of necessity but on the basis of need. It is a subtle difference but in usooli language it makes a huge difference. This is because they categorize haram in two categories. One that is haram in it of itself and one that is not. The former is given a dispensation in matters of necessity (like eating pork so you don't die), while the latter is given a dispensation in matters of need (like student loans). Riba is explicitly haram. However, aakil ar-riba and mookil ar-riba are defined under the two categories I mentioned earlier. This why the dispensation was given to student loans. Now I know I'm treading a thin line. This absolutely does not automatically apply for the business loan. And the scholars are the ones who define hajja (need). Therefore, I would defer your question to a credible scholar @Amr Aly
08-13-2017 14-00-28 Baraa Elabed @Mohamed Rashad You can't really say I heard someone say it's permissible without citing who said it and what he said

09-22-2017 21-35-40 Amir Elzomor While this situation was entirely unfortunate and deeply saddening, it served as a monumental reminder for all of us. Regardless if the accusations are true or not, that isn't for anyone here to judge or determine. Both parties claim to have substantial evidence that supports their case, and there is no way we can judge who is a liar since none of the hard facts are before us. However, let us also remember that none of us are protected from the harms of gossip and gheebah, no matter how pious. Let us remember that one of the most respectable and honorable women, Aisha (RA,) was the victim of senseless, unabashed slander when she was accused of committing zina (adultery.)
09-22-2017 21-38-29 Amir Elzomor There is a clear reason why the Islamic legal requirement for finding two people guilty of adultery is four witnesses, a seemingly impossible standard. Allah knows the evils that can overtake humanity and that too often a time people create lies and slander one another for personal gain. So to conclude, none of us here should jump to claim that NAK is guilty; however, similarly, no one should call the accusatory parties liar and dismiss all they say because that is not our position and we are ignorant of the evidence both parties claim to present. What we should do is acknowledge that the faults of one scholar do NOT caste doubts on all scholars, and that our faith and commitment to Islam is not linked to any one preacher or scholar.
09-22-2017 21-41-54 Amir Elzomor Call the accusatory parties liars**
09-22-2017 21-54-52 Chief In light of the recent events that have taken place that everyone's talking about. There's nothing wrong with respecting and admiring people of knowledge, but we have to realize that we are all human beings at the end of the day. Abu Bakr (RA) put it best after the Prophets death. "Whoever worshiped Mohammed, then Mohammed is dead. But whoever worshipped Allah, then Allah is alive and shall never die." May Allah (swt) guide us all and keep us on the straight path and to never let our Iman waver. And may He keep us away from gossip and spreading false information.

09-23-2017 20-40-41 Noor Shahin Speaking of happiness and careers before I go dark for a while I just wanted to say this, especially for the new guys and a reminder for myself too. U also proabably heard this many times before. U may make plans to become a doctor, lawyer, engineer, go to this school or this firm, or whatever. U wrote these in pencil. But Allah SWT wrote something down for you in stone. You may end up going down a slightly or completely different rode and you may not even like it, but Allah SWT knows best. It could be better for you, you could have avoided a calamity, or it could be for the benefit of others. And years later u might even be grateful you didn't follow your original very rough draft of a future u tried to plan out. Do what you can and leave the rest to Allah SWT.

10-24-2017 02-11-05 Ali Yousuf *To whom it may concern:*  Warning from Police   This is the thing these days, with people out of work and needing cash (mainly for drugs!). Beware, it's headed your way. Just last weekend on Friday night we parked in a public parking area.  As we drove away I noticed a sticker on the rear window of the car. When I got home and took it off, it was a receipt for gas. Luckily my friend had told me not to stop as it could be someone waiting for me to get out of the car.   Then we received this email yesterday: WARNING FROM POLICE: THIS APPLIES TO BOTH WOMEN AND MEN. BEWARE OF A PIECE OF PAPER ON THE BACK WINDOW OF YOUR VEHICLE (A NEW WAY TO DO CARJACKING!) (NOT A JOKE!) Heads up everyone! Please, keep this circulating.You walk across the parking lot, unlock your car and get inside. You start the engine and shift into reverse.  
10-24-2017 02-11-29 Ali Yousuf When you look into the rearview mirror to back out of your parking space, you notice a piece of paper stuck to the middle of the rear window. So, you shift into Park, unlock your doors, and jump out of your car to remove that paper (or whatever it is) that is obstructing your view.  When you reach the back of your car, that is when the carjackers appear out of nowhere, jump into your car and take off. They practically mow you down as they speed off in your car. And guess what, ladies? I bet your purse is still in the car! So now the carjacker has your car, your home address, your money, and your keys. Your home and your whole identity are now compromised! BEWARE OF THIS NEW SCHEME THAT IS NOW BEING USED.  If you see a piece of paper stuck to your back window, just drive away. Remove the paper later! And be thankful that you read this e-mail.  I hope you will forward this to friends and family, especially to women.

02-02-2018 22-48-24 Samir Hashmi Assalamu Alaykum, On February 6th, my case against the NYPD will go to the highest appeals court in New York State. As you guys are aware, this case started as a result of government surveillance on Muslim Student Associations throughout the Tri-State area. I requested files on myself because I was a Rutgers Newark MSA member. I was given a “we can neither confirm nor deny” response. I am asking everyone here to show up for support.
02-02-2018 22-48-29 Samir Hashmi This case doesn’t just affect me, it affects all of us. We all need to be more courageous in the faces of injustices that happen to us. After 14 years of service, I never asked for anything in return. If you are in this chat there is a good chance that I was your Sunday school teacher, your ICPC mentor, your fan in MYCC, and even your friend. But most importantly, I am your Muslim brother. There will always be another class to attend and another day to go work but this is your only chance to show support for this case. I will be in court at 2pm, at the court of appeals in Albany, New York. The address is 20 eagles street, Albany, New York. I hope you all can help.
02-02-2018 22-51-15 Ibraheem Othman That’s this Tuesday folks. If you’re free show support to the MSA and show the nypd who they’re dealing with!
02-02-2018 23-49-31 Amir Elzomor May Allah grant you success and Barakah in your courageous journey against injustice @Samir Hashmi . After reading into this case for the past few days, I can confidently say that this story is nothing short of courageous and inspiring. Countless hours and days have been given to fight the NYPD’s wrongful surveillance, which is a clear violation of both the First and Fourth Amendments of the US Constitution, by our Muslim brothers and sisters to stand up for all of OUR rights as Muslim Americans. Too often, we become upset and complain about injustice, however, we rarely do anything as a community to actually take action. The least we can do is show support for the Muslim brothers and sisters who are fighting this battle on behalf of all of us. Inshallah I’ll do everything I can to be there.

A teacher of mine once told me that he and a few others sat with their Shaykh in Yemen within his house, when someone knocked on the door. My teacher said, “I got up to open the door but the Shaykh stopped me and said, ‘What are you doing?’ I said, ‘I’m going to open the door’ He replied, ‘Is that it?’ I said, ‘Yes’ He said, ‘In that case, let me open the door instead’ which he did. When he came back to the study circle, the Shaykh said, ‘Your intention was to just open the door, that’s why I told you to sit down. As for me, I intended to (1) walk towards the assistance of my brother, (2) to apply the Sunnah of smiling at him, (3) to apply the Sunnah of the Islamic greeting, (4) to apply the Sunnah of handshaking, (5) to make a space for him next to me, (6) to apply the Sunnah of honouring the guest…..” and he continued listing his intentions till he’d mentioned around forty!”
02-24-2018 20-36-20 Abdelrahman Njit 2 Mu’aadh Ibnu Jabal (ra) said: أَمَّا أَنَا فَأَنَامُ وَأَقُومُ وَأَرْجُو فِي نَوْمَتِي مَا أَرْجُو فِي قَوْمَتِي “I sleep and then wake up to pray at night, and so I expect Allah to reward me for my sleep just as I expect Him to reward me for my prayer.” (Al-Bukhari) He made sure that he added a intention for his sleep – to regain strength for worship – and thus Mu’aadh anticipated reward for every second of his sleep. Perhaps after the above, you and I will never see the famous prophetic statement in the same way again, when he said: إنّمَا الأَعْمَالُ بالنِّيّاتِ، وَإِنَّمَا لِكُلِّ امرِىءٍ مَا نَوَى “Actions are by intentions, and each person shall be rewarded according to his intention” (Bukhari and muslim)
